d.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stormygalewindrunner>Stormygale Windrunner</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.cpmission.com/graphics/icons/icon09.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 586<br> <font color=#7A8798>(4/28/03 11:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Stormygale twitched in her sleep. She was dreaming of lusty Lizards, when suddenly her eyes popped open and she sat up.  She was damp and tangled in her blankets, and it took her a while to remove them so she could get up and stagger to look out the window. As she feared, it was the dead of night. No dawn. Just the cold cruel stars looking down on her like shards of glass. They held no answers for her. She was lost. <br>
<br>
Her back was on fire as she returned to her bed and sat on its twisted damp wool. She put her head in her hands and moaned.  Then she reached over to the table near the bed to grab the flask of brandy she always kept near.  She sipped as she did every night now, and every day. It helped to dull the pain, but it also dulled her mind. She really didn’t care. The blow from the dragon in the Hedge Run of the Plane of Nightmare had almost broken her back. She still hadn’t healed from it, and it caused her much pain. The brandy helped. Sometimes. If she drank enough. Oh she’d received her flag to a gateway of a plane she’d never see, but the cost had been terrible. She was now a cripple.<br>
<br>
She had taken up residence in an inn in Freeport, and had found a tavern that would deliver. No one traveled there much anymore, and she was rarely bothered.  Every day they brought her food and brandy, although she rarely ate anymore. She had no appetite, and she’d lost a lot of weight. They now brought less food and more brandy.<br>
<br>
She had not told the guild of her injury. There was nothing to be done about it anyway. Either it would heal, or it would not. She feared it would not. She had prayed to her icy God, The Lady Tunare, but Tunare had remained silent, as always. The wench. It had been many months now, and still she could barely move without fire streaking down her leg. She was unable even to stand upright, and so spent most of her time in bed. She could no longer sit in a chair without agony, and there was no way she could fight. She doubted she could even hold a shield.  For the hundredth time she looked over at her epic sword leaning carefully against the wall. She only had to fall upon it for it to all be over. In this room she rarely ever left, no one would know. There were no clerics nearby, only useless maids who did nothing but chatter. They never entered her room but once a week to change the bedding. If she timed it right, it would be too late for a cleric to help her, even if the maids called for one which was doubtful, as they were dumb as posts. <br>
<br>
She sighed. Something in her wasn’t quite ready for that final solution. Something still rebelled. For some silly reason she still had hope, but hope was a dangerous thing.  She lay back down and tried to get comfortable, still sipping her brandy. <br>
<br>
As the brandy took effect, she let her mind wander to the past. She remembered back when Norrath was new and she was so young. Life was so powerful then. Everything was so exciting with new adventures and new people to meet. People were nice back then. It was rare to run into an evil traitorous sneak. But over the years the evil-doers had become more numerous and she had become wary. She remembered very clearly the first time she’d fell to a scam in Eastern Commons. She’d lost two thousand pieces of platinum to the firepot dupe. God she was so young. So stupid back then. <br>
<br>
She remembered the first time she saw a Hill Giant in the West commons. She’d about wet herself with fear. How could anything be so BIG? And the first time she found floating swords in Kithicor Forest, before it had been changed to such a bastion of evil. It had been a beautiful wood, and she still remembered exploring it’s depths with glee.  She had no idea what Shadow Men were back then, but she had been wary of those floating swords, and had kept her distance, even camouflaged as she was.  And the first time she had ventured to that far off frozen tundra of the Barbarians and met the Lady Vox. She had been summoned and had died. But everyone had died that day. It was something that amazed her still, this power clerics had to recall a person from death. The death she craved though would be permanent. There would be no resurrection for her.  If she ever found her courage.<br>
<br>
Her guild must have thought she had abandoned them by now. And in truth, she almost had.  She was unable to attend and help with their battles, and was unable to bear the fact that she was so useless.  It was remarkable that any of them even remembered that she still existed. She felt like transparent paper. Or a Ghost. Something that showed up and wavered in the background once in a rare while, but was never seen.  Useless and hollow. She looked at her sword again, as she sipped. <br>
<br>
The worst part of her isolation was the fact that over the months, she had lost all of those people she had once called friend. They had gone. Either to another place she could not go, Stormygale being so young, or had left the world of Norrath forever.  Either way, she was truly alone.  To be guilded or not guilded at this point would hardly make a difference. Her guild had traveled on, while she had been injured. She would not catch up. In truth, she couldn’t. She had been left behind. Well, she had become used to being alone.  She had always been alone. Just her and her brandy.<br>
<br>
But she loved the Claw of Nagafen, though it tore her apart. It had become her home. Full, as it was, with such wonderful people. She admired so many of them and their astonishing ability to do what other guilds could only do with twice the people. She was proud to wear the guild tag, but felt in her heart that it was a hollow sham. She only watched the guild from afar now. She wasn’t a participant in the glorious battles that gave The Claw of Nagafen its reputation. She was a fraud.  Could she really go on wearing this tag and be truthful to her guild? She sipped some more brandy.  She had spoken of her feelings to the last friend she had on Norrath, and he had pleaded with her not to leave, as did an officer she had approached. But how could she stay and be honest? She was so torn. <br>
<br>
Again, there were no answers for her. So, she sipped her brandy and lay in her bed, and let the world revolve. More and more often, her eyes wandered to her epic sword, but her eyes grew heavy with the effects of the brandy and again, she fell asleep to dream of lusty Lizards...<br>
 <p><html>
